n configuration\n  Line 30: ### Scenario: Router creates session store with custom configuration\n  Line 32: **GIVEN** a Router instance is created with session configuration: `sessionTimeout: \"60m\"`, `sessionCookieName: \"SID\"`, `sessionMaxActive: 5000`\n  Line 36: ### Scenario: Router disables session management\n  Line 38: **GIVEN** a Router instance with `sessionEnabled: false` (default)\n  Line 47: ### Scenario: Router generates unique session ID for new session\n  Line 49: **GIVEN** a Router with session management enabled\n  Line 54: ### Scenario: Router generates unique session IDs without collision\n  Line 56: **GIVEN** a Router with session management enabled\n  Line 65: ### Scenario: Router stores session data\n  Line 67: **GIVEN** a Router with session management enabled\n  Line 72: ### Scenario: Router retrieves existing session\n  Line 74: **GIVEN** a Router with active sessions in the store\n  Line 79: ### Scenario: Router returns nil for invalid session ID\n  Line 81: **GIVEN** a Router with active sessions\n  Line 88: **GIVEN** a Router with session management enabled and `sessionMaxActive: 100`\n  Line 100: **GIVEN** a Router with session management enabled\n  Line 107: **GIVEN** a Router with session management enabled\n  Line 114: **GIVEN** a Router with session management enabled\n  Line 130: ### Scenario: Router routes request to session's assigned backend\n  Line 137: ### Scenario: Router creates new session with backend assignment\n  Line 139: **GIVEN** a Router with session management and backend pool containing backends\n  Line 144: ### Scenario: Router handles session when backend is removed\n  Line 173: ### Scenario: Router runs periodic session cleanup\n  Line 175: **GIVEN** a Router with session cleanup interval set to 5 minutes\n  Line 193: **GIVEN** a Router with `sessionCookieSecure: true` and `sessionCookieHTTPOnly: true`\n  Line 200: **GIVEN** a Router with `sessionCookieDomain: \"example.com\"`\n  Line 214: ### Scenario: Router exports active session count\n  Line 216: **GIVEN** a Router with session management and metrics enabled\n  Line 220: ### Scenario: Router tracks session creation rate\n  Line 222: **GIVEN** a Router with session management and metrics enabled\n  Line 226: ### Scenario: Router tracks session expiration rate\n  Line 228: **GIVEN** a Router with session management and metrics enabled\n  Line 232: ### Scenario: Router exports session duration histogram\n  Line 234: **GIVEN** a Router with session management and metrics enabled\n  Line 242: ### Scenario: Router closes session store on shutdown\n  Line 244: **GIVEN** a running Router with active sessions\n  Line 270: - Delta Spec: `changes/AR-010/delta-spec.md`\n\n/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md:\n  Line 1: # Proposal: AR-010 вҖ” Router дјҡиҜқз®ЎзҗҶ\n  Line 5: Implement session management capabilities in `pkg/router` to track, manage, and persist user sessions when routing to AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter backends. This enables sticky sessions, session affinity, session lifecycle management, and provides operational visibility into active sessions.\n  Line 20: Provide session management that:\n  Line 32: - Enables session expiration for resource management\n  Line 72: | SessionEnabled | bool | false | Enable session management |\n  Line 154: **Decision**: Rejected вҖ” stateless nature prevents session management features like forced logout.\n\n/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/python-sdk/design.md:\n  Line 294:     \"\"\"Raised when session creation or management fails\"\"\"\n\n/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/python-sdk/spec.md:\n  Line 98: The system SHALL use lowercase header name `x-agentcube-session-id` for SDK Router requests (`CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient` default session header; `AgentRuntimeDataPlane