{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775849176856,"sessionID":"ses_28725112effeLv38OgxzcMAJ8A","part":{"id":"prt_d78dbfb97001zrhUR07eLDjRKa","messageID":"msg_d78dbdd43001xXAEya6fTTMPxF","sessionID":"ses_28725112effeLv38OgxzcMAJ8A","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_609ea5313eb642c987d40f23","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: AR-010 вҖ” Router дјҡиҜқз®ЎзҗҶ\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement session management capabilities in `pkg/router` to track, manage, and persist user sessions when routing to AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter backends. This enables sticky sessions, session affinity, session lifecycle management, and provides operational visibility into active sessions.\n6: \n7: ## Purpose\n8: \n9: ### Background\n10: \n11: The AR-009 router implements HTTP reverse proxying to dynamically route requests to AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter sandboxes. Currently:\n12: \n13: - **No session tracking**: Requests are routed without awareness of session context\n14: - **No sticky sessions**: Load balancing distributes requests across backends without session affinity\n15: - **No session lifecycle**: No mechanism to track when sessions start/end\n16: - **No session state visibility**: No way to query active sessions or session metadata\n17: \n18: ### Goal\n19: \n20: Provide session management that:\n21: - Tracks active sessions with unique identifiers\n22: - Supports sticky sessions (session affinity based on session ID)\n23: - Manages session lifecycle (creation, expiration, cleanup)\n24: - Provides session metadata storage (user ID, backend, start time, last activity)\n25: - Enables session-based access control\n26: - Exports session metrics for monitoring\n27: \n28: ### Value\n29: - Enables consistent user experience with sticky sessions\n30: - Provides audit trail for session activity\n31: - Supports session-based rate limiting per user\n32: - Enables session expiration for resource management\n33: - Improves operational visibility\n34: \n35: ---\n36: \n37: ## Scope\n38: \n39: ### In-Scope\n40: \n41: | Deliverable | Description |\n42: |-------------|-------------|\n43: | Session Store | In-memory store for session tracking with thread-safe operations |\n44: | Session ID Generation | Generate unique session IDs (UUID or similar) |\n45: | Session Affinity | Route requests to the same backend based on session cookie/header |\n46: | Session Lifecycle | Create, update, expire, and delete sessions |\n47: | Session Middleware | HTTP middleware to extract/inject session ID |\n48: | Session Metrics | Track active sessions, session rates, expirations |\n49: | Session Configuration | Configurable session timeout, cookie name, storage options |\n50: | Unit Tests | Core session logic coverage >70% |\n51: \n52: ### Code Structure\n53: \n54: ```\n55: pkg/router/\n56: в”ңв”Җв”Җ session/\n57: в”Ӯ   в”ңв”Җв”Җ session.go           # Session struct and interface\n58: в”Ӯ   в”ңв”Җв”Җ store.go             # Session store implementation\n59: в”Ӯ   в”ңв”Җв”Җ manager.go           # Session lifecycle manager\n60: в”Ӯ   в””в”Җв”Җ config.go            # Session configuration\n61: в”ңв”Җв”Җ middleware/\n62: в”Ӯ   в””в”Җв”Җ session.go           # Session middleware for HTTP\n63: в””в”Җв”Җ (existing files...)\n64: ```\n65: \n66: ### Configuration\n67: \n68: The router supports these new session configuration options:\n69: \n70: | Option | Type | Default | Description |\n71: |--------|------|---------|-------------|\n72: | SessionEnabled | bool | false | Enable session management |\n73: | SessionTimeout | duration | 30m | Session expiration time |\n74: | SessionCookieName | string | \"AGENTSESSIONID\" | Cookie/header name for session ID |\n75: | SessionCookieDomain | string | \"\" | Cookie domain (empty = current domain) |\n76: | SessionCookieSecure | bool | true | Set Secure flag on cookie |\n77: | SessionCookieHTTPOnly | bool | true | Set HttpOnly flag on cookie |\n78: | SessionMaxActive | int | 10000 | Max concurrent sessions |\n79: | SessionCleanupInterval | duration | 5m | Interval for expired session cleanup |\n80: \n81: ### Out-of-Scope\n82: - Distributed session store (Redis, etcd) вҖ” future enhancement\n83: - Session persistence to Kubernetes CRD вҖ” future enhancement\n84: - Session replication across router instances\n85: - OIDC/OAuth2 session integration (use existing auth middleware)\n86: \n87: ---\n88: \n89: ## Impact Analysis\n90: \n91: ### Dependencies\n92: \n93: | Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n94: |------------|--------|---------|\n95: | github.com/google/uuid | ^1.6 | Session ID generation |\n96: | github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1 | local | CR types for session correlation |\n97: | github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/pkg/router | local | Existing router module |\n98: \n99: ### Upstream Dependencies\n100: \n101: - **AR-009 Router Core** вҖ” Provides the reverse proxy foundation\n102: - **AR-007 K8s Reconciler** вҖ” Creates backends that sessions connect to\n103: \n104: ### Downstream Consumers\n105: \n106: 1. **External Clients** вҖ” Benefit from sticky sessions and consistent experience\n107: 2. **Monitoring Systems** вҖ” Session metrics for operational visibility\n108: 3. **Auth System** вҖ” Session-based access control integration\n109: \n110: ### Risks\n111: \n112: | Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n113: |------|----------|------------|\n114: | Memory exhaustion | Medium | Max session limit, automatic cleanup |\n115: | Session hijacking | Medium | Secure cookies, server-side session storage |\n116: | Session race conditions | Low | Thread-safe store implementation |\n117: | Cookie manipulation | Medium | Validate session ID format, server-side lookup |\n118: \n119: ---\n120: \n121: ## Alternatives Considered\n122: \n123: ### Option 1: Cookie-Based Session with Backend Affinity (Selected)\n124: \n125: **Approach**: Use HTTP cookies to track session ID, route to the same backend based on session mapping.\n126: \n127: **Pros**:\n128: - Simple client integration (browser handles cookies)\n129: - Works with existing routing layer\n130: - Low overhead for session tracking\n131: \n132: **Cons**:\n133: - Requires cookie support in client\n134: - Sticky sessions may cause uneven load\n135: \n136: **Decision**: Selected вҖ” provides the best balance of simplicity and functionality.\n137: \n138: ---\n139: \n140: ### Option 2: JWT-Based Session Management\n141: \n142: **Approach**: Use JWT tokens containing session claims, validate at router level.\n143: \n144: **Pros**:\n145: - Stateless, no server-side storage needed\n146: - Built-in expiration\n147: - Cryptographically verified\n148: \n149: **Cons**:\n150: - Cannot revoke active sessions\n151: - Larger token size\n152: - More complex implementation\n153: \n154: **Decision**: Rejected вҖ” stateless nature prevents session management features like forced logout.\n155: \n156: ---\n157: \n158: ### Option 3: External Session Store (Redis)\n159: \n160: **Approach**: Store sessions in Redis for distributed access.\n161: \n162: **Pros**:\n163: - Shared state across router instances\n164: - Persistence beyond process lifetime\n165: \n166: **Cons**:\n167: - Adds external dependency\n168: - Network latency for session operations\n169: - Additional infrastructure requirement\n170: \n171: **Decision**: Rejected вҖ” adds complexity; in-memory store suffices for single-instance deployment.\n172: \n173: ---\n174: \n175: ### Option 4: Client-Side Session (URL Rewriting)\n176: \n177: **Approach**: Encode session ID in URL paths.\n178: \n179: **Pros**:\n180: - Works without cookies\n181: \n182: **Cons**:\n183: - URL pollution\n184: - Security concerns\n185: - Not suitable for REST APIs\n186: \n187: **Decision**: Rejected вҖ” not appropriate for API-focused routing.\n188: \n189: ---\n190: \n191: ## Implementation Plan\n192: \n193: ### Phase 1: Session Core\n194: - [ ] Define Session struct with ID, UserID, Backend, StartTime, LastActivity, Metadata\n195: - [ ] Implement SessionStore interface with thread-safe operations\n196: - [ ] Implement in-memory SessionStore with map and RWMutex\n197: - [ ] Add session ID generation (UUID v4)\n198: \n199: ### Phase 2: Session Middleware\n200: - [ ] Extract session ID from cookie or X-Session-ID header\n201: - [ ] Create new session if not exists (when SessionEnabled)\n202: - [ ] Inject session cookie in response\n203: - [ ] Update last activity on each request\n204: \n205: ### Phase 3: Session Affinity\n206: - [ ] Modify RouteHandler to check session affinity\n207: - [ ] Store backend key in session\n208: - [ ] Route to stored backend when session exists\n209: - [ ] Handle backend removal with session invalidation\n210: \n211: ### Phase 4: Session Lifecycle\n212: - [ ] Implement session expiration checking\n213: - [ ] Add background goroutine for cleanup\n214: - [ ] Handle session deletion on backend removal\n215: - [ ] Add configuration for timeout and limits\n216: \n217: ### Phase 5: Metrics and Observability\n218: - [ ] Add session counter (active, created, expired)\n219: - [ ] Add session rate metrics\n220: - [ ] Add session duration histogram\n221: - [ ] Export session metrics to Prometheus\n222: \n223: ### Phase 6: Testing\n224: - [ ] Unit tests for SessionStore operations\n225: - [ ] Unit tests for session middleware\n226: - [ ] Unit tests for session affinity\n227: - [ ] Mock tests for session lifecycle\n228: \n229: ---\n230: \n231: ## Acceptance Criteria\n232: \n233: - [ ] Session store supports create, get, update, delete operations\n234: - [ ] Session ID is generated as UUID v4\n235: - [ ] Session cookie is set on first request when enabled\n236: - [ ] Subsequent requests with same cookie route to same backend\n237: - [ ] Sessions expire after configured timeout\n238: - [ ] Expired sessions are cleaned up automatically\n239: - [ ] Session metrics are exported (active_sessions, session_created_total, session_expired_total)\n240: - [ ] Max session limit is enforced\n241: - [ ] Session data includes user ID, backend, start time, last activity\n242: - [ ] Unit tests pass with >70% coverage\n243: - [ ] Graceful shutdown closes session store\n\n(End of file - total 243 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: AR-010 вҖ” Router дјҡиҜқз®ЎзҗҶ\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement session management capabilities in `pkg/router` to track, manage, and persist user sessions when routing to AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter backends. This enables sticky sessions, session affinity, session lifecycle management, and provides operational visibility into active sessions.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe AR-009 router implements HTTP reverse proxying to dynamically route requests to AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter sandboxes. Currently:\n\n- **No session tracking**: Requests are routed without awareness of session context\n- **No sticky sessions**: Load balancing distributes requests across backends without session affinity\n- **No session lifecycle**: No mechanism to track when sessions start/end\n- **No session state visibility**: No way to query active sessions or session metadata\n\n### Goal\n\nProvide session management that:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775849176838,"end":1775849176853}}}}
